<TEXT>
californias presidential primary 
would be advanced from june to the first tuesday in march under 
legislation approved wednesday by a twohouse conference committee 
of the state legislature 
the proposal sent to the floors of both houses for final votes 
before their aug 31 adjournment would place californias primary 
just one week after new hampshires firstinthe nation primary 
california political leaders of both parties support the change 
saying it would transform the primary from a political afterthought 
in the presidential sweepstakes to what could be the dominant early 
primary 
were trying to become a stronger player in national 
politics state sen ken maddy of fresno the republican leader 
in the senate said wednesday 
however the 50 vote of the twohouse committee for the early 
primary plan still doesnt assure its passage assembly speaker 
willie brown a democrat said the shift wouldnt be approved in 
unless it won support from all the party leaders in both house 
maddy said he and many republican legislators prefer a plan that 
moves the presidential primary to march and all other primaries to 
september the plan sent to the senate and assembly floors leaves 
the other primaries on the first tuesday in june the same date as 
the presidential primary 
the last time the state proved crucial in the primaries was 
1972 when george mcgovern used his victory over hubert humphrey to 
capture the nomination at the national democratic convention barry 
goldwaters victory over nelson rockefeller in californias 1964 
primary was the last time the state played a role in picking the 
gop nominee for president 
the lack of influence rankles many in the state especially 
because california sends by far the largest delegations to both 
national conventions 
supporters of the measure sponsored by democratic assemblyman 
jim costa say that because of the states late primary 
presidential hopefuls of both parties ignore california except for 
brief visits to raise money for their races in new hampshire iowa 
and other early primary and caucus states 
opponents of the move say it would favor wellheeled 
presidential candidates giving those who can raise early campaign 
contributions an edge in the nations largest state 
the dispute over whether to leave californias congressional 
legislative and other primaries in june or shift them to september 
involves complicated and obscure tactical considerations political 
strategists argue about which party would benefit from shortening 
the period between the primary and general election from five to 
two months 
</TEXT>
