<DOCNO> AP900822-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
they were just four of the millions who 
perished in nazi camps but in the shadow of death the jewish 
composers created a musical legacy that has outlived the horror of 
their fates 
today a musician is organizing performances of the almost 
forgotten pieces by gideon klein pavel haas viktor ullmann and 
hans krasa musicians imprisoned in a concentration camp in 
nazioccupied czechoslovakia 
its amazing and its inspiring says mark ludwig a boston 
symphony orchestra violist our mission is to make the public 
aware not only of the great talents of these artists but theres a 
spiritual resistance a spiritual form of resistance which is also 
very inspiring 
ludwig spent two years tracking down scores from composers at 
the nazi camp in terezin czechoslovakia a village north of 
prague he concentrated on the four composers who had promising 
careers in prewar prague krasas first symphony for example 
had been performed by the boston orchestra in 1926 
many of the scores came from the state jewish museum in prague 
and the terezin national monument where they had been deposited 
after the war and largely ignored others came from survivors 
entrusted with the music 
some of the pieces mainly chamber music express a great deal 
of pain and desolation ludwig said there are also others that 
are reminiscent of times past good times if you will a way of 
momentarily distracting the audience from their environment 
people are just so moved by the power because the soul is 
coming out he said during a recent interview at the orchestras 
summer home you dont have to be so sophisticated it just 
touches you its so deeply felt 
the concentration camp known as theresienstadt originally was a 
walled garrison town the camp served as a way station for 
transports to death camps in the east and as the center of a nazi 
propaganda effort 
at the camp the musical community sometimes had to keep out of 
sight holding rehearsals in attics and basements of the town 
after they learned of the makeshift concerts nazi guards at 
first allowed them as part of their efforts to create the 
appearance of a model camp later the cultural activities often 
were forbidden as a disciplinary measure 
ullmann wrote a short allegorical opera about life in the camp 
which was rehearsed but was not allowed to be performed ludwig 
said the composer almost took the score with him when he was sent 
to auschwitz but was persuaded by friends to leave the music 
behind 
to bring the music before the public ludwig founded the 
nonprofit terezin chamber music foundation so far concerts have 
been held in worcester and at a holocaust memorial service at the 
massachusetts statehouse concerts are planned next year for 
amsterdam boston and the berkshires 
the pieces mainly short works such as string trios quartets 
and sonatas carry melodic slavic influences and ludwig believes 
are destined to become part of chamber musics repertoire 
next years programs include music that hasnt been heard since 
it was first written and performed in the concentration camp a 
time when the musicians probably were never sure of their fate 
ludwig said 
you still hold that hope when you think about it creativity 
thats a form of hope too even in a horrendous environment in 
the worst of times if one is creating one is expressing there is 
a need theres a hope 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900822-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
iraqs invasion of kuwait has forced 
saudi arabia to make a fundamental and perhaps permanent change in 
its public approach to the outside world 
the invasion forced saudi arabia long equivocal about its links 
with the west to publicly ally itself with the united states 
despised by many arabs for its support of israel the united arab 
emirates and other persian gulf states have followed saudi king 
fahds lead declaring their support for us forces on their soil 
for more than four decades the saudis have tried to conceal 
their close economic cooperation with americans and the us 
military presence in the cradle of islam but the aug 2 overthrow 
of kuwaits royal family the oldest dynasty in the gulf region 
underlined the fragility of the gulf kingdoms and sheikdoms 
saudi unease had already been triggered by the collapse of the 
shah of iran in the 1979 islamic revolution across the gulf 
king fahd had little choice in the face of iraqi president 
saddam husseins military actions but to call in the americans and 
their allies to protect his kingdom and its vast oil fields 
the only alternative was unthinkable to sit back and watch 
saddam overrun the united arab emirates qatar and eventually 
saudi arabia itself said an arab diplomat who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
despite lavishing billions of dollars on sophisticated military 
hardware over the years king fahds untested 120000strong armed 
forces are no match against saddams battleseasoned hordes 
like other arab rulers the saudi royal family saw that 
grassroots support for saddam among the regions 200 million 
arabs long envious of the gulfs oil riches was a mushrooming 
radical force 
since king abdulaziz founded the alsaud dynasty in the 1920s 
by conquering rival bedouin clans and forging the saudi state his 
descendants policy has been survival at any cost 
like other gulf oil states the saudis have long avoided discord 
by sheltering behind their islamic piety and consensus politics 
us ties date back to 1945 when abdulaziz made an unwritten 
alliance with the united states the americans edging out the 
british secured the first oil concessions in 1933 giving 
washington strategic interests in saudi arabia 
fahd told his estimated 8 million subjects two weeks ago that he 
had invited the americans to help him reinstate the alsabahs in 
kuwait and defend saudi arabia against a possible iraqi attack 
since then the americans have been pouring troops and materiel 
into saudi arabia fahd has sought to placate his islamic critics 
these forces from friendly powers are here temporarily and 
will leave as soon as the kingdom so demands he stressed in a 
nationwide statement aug 9 he reiterated it aug 21 
but with saddam deploying an estimated 200000 men in and around 
kuwait and showing no sign of pulling out of the former emirate 
the americans may be around for awhile 
everyone accepts that theres going to be a longterm american 
military presence said a senior gulf official who spoke on 
condition he was not named its no secret that saudi arabia and 
other gulf countries willingly accept whatever it takes to ensure 
their stability if necessary they will accept an increased 
american presence here 
thats a dramatic aboutface for the saudis who have long 
sought to play down their western orientation while paying lip 
service to arab nationalism and the palestinians struggle against 
israel 
the saudi rulers have overseen the transformation of a desert 
backwater into a modern state all the time trying to prevent 
progress from undermining its islamic roots 
much of the royal familys legitimacy rests on islam a few 
years ago fahd stressed this by declaring himself the guardian of 
islams holiest shrines at mecca and medina 
allowing american infidels in to protect the holy places has 
drawn resentment from moslem quarters 
libyan leader moammar gadhafi has for years berated the saudis 
for befriending the united states and urged moslems to stop making 
the annual pilgrimage to mecca as long as it remains under 
american military occupation 
irans islamic revolutionaries have constantly reviled the saudi 
leaders as american stooges and called for the downfall of the 
royal family 
the saudis have long discouraged outsiders peering into their 
world the thousands of westerners americans and others who keep 
the oil flowing live mostly in their own compounds 
that too may be changing with thousands of american gis 
flooding into the onceveiled kingdom 
american and other western journalists have been allowed in and 
events in saudi arabia are now daily on primetime television 
saudi newspapers which until recently ignored controversial 
subjects are now reporting the harsh realities facing the kingdom 
arab reporters however have been advised to refer to the us 
presence as part of a multinational force comprising egyptian 
moroccan and other arab units as well 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

