<DOCNO> AP900822-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
about 300 romanians were pulled off a 
train by bulgarian authorities after bulgaria imposed travel 
restrictions because of a cholera outbreak in romania 
dimitar dimitrov bulgarias consul in bucharest said tuesday 
that the new restrictions were imposed to protect bulgarians 
against the cholera epidemic which broke out last month in 
romanias danube delta area 
seventyfour cases have been reported in the danube region since 
midjuly thirtyone victims are still hospitalized 
dimitrov said the travel restrictions would allow individual 
romanian travelers to transit through bulgaria for no longer than 
30 hours they are also prohibited from bringing romanian 
foodstuffs or beverages into the country 
those traveling in organized group tours which typically 
provide room and board will be able to stay in bulgaria for longer 
periods dimitrov said 
on tuesday a group of 300 romanian tourists most of them 
gypsies were taken off a train by bulgarian authorities at the 
russegirgiu border crossing because of the new regulations the 
bulgarian state news agency bta reported 
some scuffled with police who tried to put them onto a train 
back to romania the romanians pulled the emergency brake on the 
return train and jumped off scattering before police could stop 
them bta said 
the news agency said the romanians also were carrying large 
quantities of goods apparently to be sold on the black market 
east germany and czechoslovakia have both imposed travel 
restrictions on romanians many romanians travel abroad to buy or 
sell goods or to seek better living standards 
bulgaria is a major transit route for romanians who travel to 
turkey for purchasing goods some of which are sold on the 
romanian black market 
under the bulgarian government decree bulgarians are 
temporarily banned from private travel to romania 
</TEXT>
