<TEXT>
at least 35000 us troops are now in saudi 
arabia or on their way and more will be going says the air force 
general in charge of getting troops to the desert kingdom 
the estimate tuesday by gen hansford t johnson while not 
precise was the clearest official indication of the size of the 
us military buildup which president bush ordered in response to 
iraqs invasion of kuwait three weeks ago 
johnson commander of the us transportation command and 
military airlift command told reporters that the equivalent of 1 
billion pounds of military equipment and soldiers had been shipped 
from us shores to the saudi desert 
he said that was comparable to ferrying 400000 us automobiles 
over that distance 
johnson said military security rules prevented him from 
disclosing the exact number of soldiers or amount of equipment that 
have been sent to saudi arabia but he said weve moved in 
essence the equivalent of a town the size of jefferson city mo 
the population of jefferson city is 35408 according to the 
preliminary 1990 census 
weve also moved all of their equipment cars trucks 
foodstuffs stocks household goods and water supply johnson 
said 
in addition to the us ground forces in saudi arabia an 
estimated 20000 sailors are deployed on warships in the persian 
gulf the arabian sea the red sea and the mediterranean as part of 
operation desert shield to defend against a possible iraqi attack 
johnson said he could not discuss planned additional 
deployments but pentagon sources have said contingency plans call 
for sending as many as 250000 troops depending on iraqi military 
moves 
