<DOCNO> AP900822-0023 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
health services and educational programs for 
rural americans at high risk of getting aids must be expanded 
dramatically to stem the spread of the disease the national 
commission on aids says 
aids education is virtually nonexistent and desperately 
needed in rural communities the commission said in a report to 
the white house and congressional leaders tuesday 
this absence of information about aids has fanned an epidemic 
of fear and bigotry in rural america where people infected with 
the aids virus fear being found out nearly as much as they fear 
the disease itself the panel said 
physicians and other healthcare professionals across the 
country also must be educated about acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome because too many of them are refusing to treat aids 
patients the commissions report said 
another area of concern to the commission was access to 
experimental drugs which panel members said is extremely limited 
for minorities women and children even those who have no other 
hope 
the 15member commission that advises congress and the white 
house urged swift action on its latest recommendations as it did 
for its recommendations in two previous reports 
were very late in responding to a massive problem but 
getting later makes no sense at all said dr june osborn 
commission chairwoman and dean of the university of michigan school 
of public health 
the 13page report drew from the commissions visits to georgia 
and texas panel members heard from people who had been rejected by 
their church lost their jobs and were evicted from their 
apartments because they were infected with hiv the human 
immunodeficiency virus that causes aids 
ignorance and misinformation are seriously hampering if not 
crippling efforts to treat rural americans with hiv infection and 
aids the report said 
aids is a more severe problem in the cities but the epidemic is 
growing faster in rural areas cases of the disease rose 37 percent 
in rural areas compared with 5 percent in metropolitan areas with 
more than half a million people from 1988 to 1989 the report said 
the commission recognized recent federal efforts to include more 
blacks and hispanics in governmentfunded testing of experimental 
drugs but said we can and must do better 
blacks and hispanics account for 43 percent of all aids cases 
but they make up only 23 percent of clinical trial participants 
the report said 
children and women of childbearing age usually have been 
excluded from clinical trials but the panel said that must change 
the report also said the national institutes of health had moved 
too slowly to find drugs to manage opportunistic infections which 
are the cause of death for most aids patients the panel said nih 
should give that research a higher priority while continuing work 
on drugs that act on the aids virus 
turning to healthcare personnel the commission said it heard 
repeatedly about a serious shortage of dentists willing to treat 
people with hiv infection and aids 
the report related the experiences of one witness who said the 
only two dentists in his community who would accept medicaid 
declined to see him because he was infected with hiv 
one dentists excuse was that his office was carpeted and he 
would not be able to sterilize the room after the visit the other 
dentist said she had plants and could not take the risk of him 
infecting her plants and her plants then infecting her other 
patients the report said 
the commission also recommended creation of a comprehensive 
communitybased primary health care system supported by adequate 
funding and reimbursement rates such a system is essential for 
the care and treatment of all people not just those with aids 
the panel said 
however the panel did not outline the specifics of such a 
system 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

