<TEXT>
nearly three weeks after iraqs invasion 
of kuwait the first signs are showing of a gathering economic 
crisis in the developing world 
in nepal theres a run on gasoline and gas prices have 
increased 50 percent in zambia sri lanka is worried about access 
to the persian gulf states who are major purchases of tea its 
principal foreign exchange earner 
scores of oilpoor and cashstrapped nations face inflation 
slower growth and increased debt after iraq invaded kuwait causing 
crude prices to rise from about 20 a barrel to more than 25 
the worst hit are the smaller and poorer nations of the world 
for whom increasing oil prices and un sanctions on trade with 
iraq and kuwait will drastically disrupt their already tenuous 
balance of payments 
manpowerexporting countries ranging from the philippines to 
egypt risk suffering rising unemployment and declining foreign 
exchange gained by workers sending part of their paychecks home 
if their citizens lose jobs in iraq and kuwait 
we could have an economic crisis of calamitous proportions 
especially if a shooting war starts in the gulf says iz 
bhatty a member of an economic think tank in new delhi oil is a 
product which has the most linkages with the rest of the economy 
many of these nations have little or no capacity for refining 
crude oil so they were ready buyers of petroleum products from 
kuwait which had the most advanced refineries in the gulf 
the pinch is also being felt in eastern europe where several 
countries have given iraq large export credits and have little hope 
of cashing in on the debt 
here are some of the countries affected and how theyre trying 
to cope 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
bangladesh the government has announced restrictions on fuel 
consumption and shops have been ordered to close by 8 pm to 
conserve electricity 
bangladesh receives at least 100 million annally from citizens 
working in iraq and kuwait about 12 percent of its total 
remittances the country would face enormous unemployment if these 
110000 people return home 
</TEXT>
