<TEXT>
figures for july show the government heading 
toward a possible new record deficit 
the 1891 billion deficit so far during the first 10 months of 
fiscal 1990 already surpassed the entire 1521 billion imbalance 
piled up during the previous year the treasury department said 
tuesday 
and it has only 32 billion to go in the next two months to beat 
the 2211 billion record set in 1986 it is already 529 percent 
above the 1237 billion deficit compiled at the end of the first 
10 months of 1989 
the white house office of management and budget in july forecast 
a 2185 billion deficit when the current fiscal year ends sept 30 
louis crandall an economist with rh wrightson amp associates in 
new york said that much of the concern over the deficit trend 
this year has been because of weakness in receipts 
however he noted that revenues in july totaled 724 billion 
up 93 percent from the comparable month last year and said that 
doesnt seem to be getting worse 
nevertheless while individual tax revenues rose corporate tax 
revenues dropped illustrating the weak economy 
and the overall receipts were more than offset by spending which 
rose 164 percent to 983 billion 
the outlays included 32 billion by the resolution trust corp 
the government agency charged with bailing out the savings and loan 
industry the sampl bailout cost 158 billion in june and 352 
billion so far this year 
the government expects to regain much of the bailout cost by 
selling real estate loans securities and other assets from failed 
thrifts that the government says will help reduce the deficit in 
future years 
in addition to spending on the thrift bailout economist 
crandall noted other very strong spending in many categories 
particularly medicare and medicaid 
spending by the health finance administration which administers 
both programs was 25 percent higher in july than a year ago 
crandall said 
revenues for the first 10 months of fiscal 1990 totaled 8501 
billion up 43 percent from the same period of 1989 but spending 
totaled 104 trillion a 107 percent increase over the first 10 
months of last year 
the biggest spending categories as usual were the military 
social security and other programs of the department of health and 
human services and interest on the national debt 
military spending totaled 22 billion in july and 2414 so far 
this year it is projected to total 2902 billion for the entire 
fiscal year 
social security payments amounted to 196 billion for the month 
and 2031 billion for the year so far they are projected to total 
2449 billion for the year 
other hhs payments including medicare and medicaid totaled 
173 billion during july and 1614 billion thus far this year 
they are projected to total 1924 billion in fiscal 1990 
interest on the national debt amounted to 184 billion for the 
month and 2286 billion so far this year it is projected to total 
2611 billion for the entire year 
