<TEXT>
john m stalnaker a psychologist who 
founded and was president of the national merit scholarship corp 
has died at age 87 
stalnaker who died at his home sunday of lymphatic cancer 
taught psychology developed tests and handled administrative 
duties at the universities of chicago and minnesota and purdue 
princeton and stanford 
at princeton stalnaker originated and operated the national 
pepsicola scholarship program forerunner of the national merit 
scholarship he helped develop that project as a consultant to the 
ford foundation 
today the nonprofit organization channels scholarship money 
from 425 corporations and foundations and 200 colleges and 
universities to more than 30000 students eight thousand high 
school students are selected each year for the program 
after the merit program was established as an independent 
corporation in 1955 he was named its first president a position 
he held until his retirement in 1969 
he also was associate director of the college entrance 
examination board from 1936 to 1945 
during world war ii stalnaker directed the armynavy college 
qualifying test and other examinations president lyndon johnson 
appointed him to the board of foreign scholarships which he served 
as chairman from 1962 to 1965 
in 1964 he became the first director of presidential 
scholarship program 
survivors include his wife edna a daughter two sons and a 
sister 
funeral services will be private 
