<DOCNO> AP900822-0044 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
boys are just as likely as girls to have 
reading disabilities but are more likely to be diagnosed by 
teachers as having the handicap because of their rambunctiousness 
says a study published today 
the very commonly held notion that there are more reading 
disabled boys than girls is really not an accurate one said dr 
sally e shaywitz an associate professor of pediatrics at the yale 
school of medicine 
more boys than girls wind up in special education classes 
apparently because of the longheld and mistaken belief that 
overactivity and other behavior problems go hand in hand with the 
learning problem the study said 
the result has been that some boys who typically are more 
rambuctious than girls are wrongly being labeled reading 
disabled shaywitz said 
at the same time some girls and some boys are not receiving 
the help they need because they show no behavior problems shaywitz 
said 
shaywitz and her fellow researchers followed more than 400 
children from 12 towns in connecticut from kindergarten through the 
third grade the findings were reported in todays journal of the 
american medical association 
tests showed that roughly the same number of boys as girls had a 
reading disability but two to four times as many boys were placed 
in special reading classes 
dr james kavanagh deputy director for the center for research 
for mothers and children in bethesda md welcomed the study but 
said more work is needed 
its done carefully and it makes good sense he said our 
conventional wisdom has always said that boys have more of these 
problems 
about 2 million children in the united states are designated as 
learning disabled most are found to have a reading disability 
defined as a reading problem that cant be explained by a students 
intellectual ability she said 
students with dyslexia for example often reverse their letters 
or have trouble with their memory or visual perception that makes 
reading difficult children with dyslexia can be taught to read 
when their disorder is recognized 
the study found a possible explanation for the mislabeling in 
the way teachers view the behavior of boys and girls 
children who were identified by their schools as reading 
disabled but who did not meet the researchers criteria were 
significantly more likely to show behavior problems conversely 
children who needed special reading help but were well behaved 
tended to be overlooked by the system the study found 
the schools identified 27 of 198 secondgrade boys and seven of 
216 secondgrade girls as reading disabled by the third grade 20 
of 199 boys were labeled reading disabled by their schools 
compared to nine of 215 girls 
meanwhile the researchers found 13 or 45 percent of the 
thirdgraders receiving special education didnt have a reading 
disability after all 
by putting the wrong labels on the wrong individuals people 
