<DOCNO> AP900822-0076 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
purdue university researchers 
believe they have unlocked a key in the battle against alcoholism 
they have isolated a chunk of a hormone that makes the body feel 
good after drinking alcohol 
graduate student suchitra a krishnan studied rats who were 
placed under stress and then allowed to drink alcohol under both 
conditions they produced the adrenocorticotrophic hormone or acth 
we think a fragment of the hormone is responsible for making 
the rats want to drink alcohol after the stress is relieved even 
if they were low or nondrinkers before apparently they learn to 
drink to reproduce the good feeling said krishnan 
krishnan presented her findings tuesday at the 21st congress of 
the international society of psychoneuroendocrinology in buffalo 
ny 
krishnan and pharmacy professor roger p maickel said that if a 
drug containing the same amino acids as the feel good section 
of acth were given to alcoholics it might satisfy their desire to 
drink without alcohols many bad side effects 
in the study krishnan gauged the rats alcohol consumption by 
letting them drink from either of two bottles of sweetened water 
one containing 10 percent alcohol then the rats were divided into 
two groups made up of low moderate and heavy alcohol consumers 
krishnan caused stress among one group by closely confining them 
for periods of time over several days during the confinement the 
animals all drank less alcohol than each one had before being 
stressed but after the stress ended they generally drank two to 
three times more alcohol than before 
a second group of rats was not stressed but was injected with a 
piece of the acth molecule called acth410 for several days most 
drank no alcohol during that time but several days after the 
injections stopped they began drinking at twice to three times the 
rate they had before 
the acth410 acts like a reward mechanism to the rats 
krishnan said for the most part they didnt want to drink 
alcohol at all during the injections because they were already 
getting a substantial dose of the fragment 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

