<TEXT>
operation push has failed to win support from 
black leaders in portland ore after two days of protests and 
meetings on its boycott of oregonbased nike inc 
push wasnt happy it could not rally local support robert 
phillips president of the portland naacp said tuesday 
leaders of the portland branches of the naacp the black united 
front the urban league and the coalition of black men met monday 
with push executive director tyrone crider joining crider were 
chicago alderman dorothy tillman and other activists who flew to 
oregon to garner support for the boycott 
about 150 people attended a rally monday night about 40 of them 
were push supporters from chicago and several portland residents 
said they had come more out of curiosity than sympathy with the 
boycott 
black community leaders in the portland area said the boycott is 
illconceived and lacks leadership they expressed anger that 
chicagobased push ignored them before forging ahead with its war 
against nike the nations largest athletic shoe maker 
push called for the boycott two weeks ago saying nike denies 
blacks adequate employment and business opportunities nike based 
in suburban beaverton says its policies and programs for 
minorities could be models for the industry 
push which originally stood for people united to save humanity 
was founded by jesse jackson he gave up direct leadership of the 
organization to run for president in 1984 and more recently has 
left its board 
