the columbus ohio dispatch on genetic engineering 
more than 100 genetically engineered drugs vaccines and other 
substances have been approved by the food and drug administration 
these have been used against diabetes and hemophilia among other 
things in recent years the good they have done is incalculable 
but there is a downside too particularly when a genetically 
engineered substance is not considered a drug and therefore does 
not come under close fda scrutiny 
and that is what happened with tainted ltryptophan that last 
year killed 27 and injured 1500 americans the genetically 
engineered bacterium developed by a janapese drug company showa 
denko kk was widely used as a nutritional supplement and sleep 
aid 
in the genetic engineering process its believed a byproduct 
called peak e was produced which may cause ems a rare and 
sometimes fatal blood disease 
although bacteria have been used for years in the manufacture of 
biologically active substances only since 1975 have there been 
manmade alterations in the genetic structures of common bacteria 
this may be the first known example of biotechnology gone awry 
but even so it raises serious questions about the nations growing 
biotechnology industry should there be more supervision if so 
should the government do it 
fda officials have said the growing use of genetic engineering 
in the manufacture of drugs and dietary products is something the 
agency plans to look at in the future 
lets hope the agency does this before another accident produces 
deadly results 
