<TEXT>
at least 13 congressmen belong to national 
guard or military reserve units but they cant be called to active 
duty unless they first give up their seats 
any time there is a mobilization of guard and reserve units the 
pentagon automatically puts members of congress and other top 
government officials who are reservists or guardsmen on standby 
their name is in a computer thats about all it amounts to 
said a congressional staffer who didnt want his name used 
to see active military duty whether combat or a war of nerves 
with iraqs saddam hussein members of congress would have to first 
surrender their seats 
rep dave mccurdy dokla a captain and member of the judge 
advocates corps in the air force reserve said lawmakers werent 
likely to resign for a limited callup 
if there is an acknowledged war and the entire nation is 
mobilized mccurdy said i think well all go 
seven of mccurdys colleagues are in the reserves and five more 
are active in their state national guard units all fall under 
federal guidelines that require officials in line of succession to 
the presidency members of congress and other key officials to 
transfer from ready to standby reserve status 
they may participate in drills and training exercises and 
collect points for retirement pensions but they cannot be paid or 
activated 
rep thomas carper ddel a navy reserve commander and 
decorated flight officer in the vietnam war said he had to get a 
waiver from the chief of naval operations to keep flying and 
maintain his status as a qualified mission commander aboard a p3 
surveillance plane the type of aircraft now tracking merchant 
shipping to and from iraq 
when i was elected in 1982 i learned i could no longer hold a 
mobilization billet even though im a member of a combatready 
patrol squadron carper said 
former rep john o marsh jr a virginia democrat and later 
secretary of the army was the last lawmaker to go to war while 
still holding a seat in congress he was a major in the virginia 
national guard when he volunteered to spend a 30day activeduty 
tour in vietnam during a 1966 congressional christmas recess 
i got on a regular lift just like any other replacement troops 
going over he said only a few people there knew i was a 
member of congress the agreement i had with the chief of staff of 
the army was there would be no publicity 
since the civil war presidents and members of congress alike 
have recognized an inherent conflict in having lawmakers who 
exercise civilian control and oversight of the military 
simultaneously serve under military commanders 
president lincoln prohibited his generals from allowing 
lawmakers to join them in combat after his close friend sen 
edward baker rore crossed the potomac to take part in the 
battle of balls bluff and was killed 
denied a leave of absence for a second tour of duty in world war 
ii republican henry cabot lodge of massachusetts gave up his seat 
in congress in 1944 to join the fighting in europe he had been 
granted one senate leave to serve in 1942 with american tank crews 
in libya 
but after other lawmakers including a thenjunior house 
democrat from texas lyndon johnson demanded cameo appearance 
tours the war department in 1943 stopped activating sitting 
members of congress 
its a pretty basic conflict of interest said senate 
historian richard a baker it was inconveniencing a lot of 
people and there was a big concern that a lot of it was being done 
for political considerations 
there was also the concern that services would use reserve 
promotions to reward legislators for shepherding projects or 
weapons systems through the complex authorization and 
appropriations webs of congress 
i dont think in this day and age that you can serve two 
masters said rep bill mccollum rfla also a navy reserve 
commander 
