<TEXT>
sri lankan troops landed on rebelheld 
jaffna peninsula by ship wednesday and began advancing on a 
government fort that has been besieged by rebels for the past 10 
weeks officials said 
a western diplomat said it was the first movement by government 
troops in six weeks on the peninsula a key stronghold of the rebel 
tamil tigers militia 
the diplomat called the move a significant offensive but 
said government forces were in no position to unleash a knockout 
blow against the rebels the diplomat spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
authorities said ships ferried 750 to 1000 troops to a naval 
base in the north the troops then launched an offensive to relieve 
the garrison trapped in jaffna fort the naval base is about 12 
miles from the 200yearold fort 
jaffna 186 miles northeast of the capital of colombo is the 
headquarters of the liberation tigers of tamil eelam the major 
rebel group fighting for tamil independence from the ethnic 
sinhalesedominated government 
government planes tuesday dropped leaflets on jaffna announcing 
an indefinite curfew and warning the 850000 civilians there that 
the government would mount air strikes against rebel positions 
most civilians on the peninsula are tamils 
the curfew took effect at 600 am wednesday and warplanes 
began bombing runs one hour later said the officials who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
the bombing apparently was a diversionary tactic while the naval 
vessels landed the troops ashore the officials said 
army commander lt gen hamilton wanasinghe flew to jaffna to 
supervise the operation the military said 
in a statement released by his office deputy defense minister 
ranjan wijeratne assured diplomats there would be no indiscriminate 
bombing of civilians and that any action would be taken only 
after careful intelligence assessment to minimize any loss of 
civilian life 
but a western diplomat said sri lankas small illequipped air 
force has nothing that is able to pound tiger positions with any 
degree of precision 
at least 14000 people have died since the rebels took up arms 
against the government 
the tigers who have accused the government of discrimination 
against ethnic tamils are demanding an independent state in the 
north and east where tamils are most numerous 
tamils who are mostly hindus constitute 18 percent of the 
population of this indian ocean island while sinhalese who are 
mostly buddhist make up 85 percent of the population and dominate 
the military and government 
jaffna fort was surrounded june 11 when the tigers broke a 
13month ceasefire and resumed their sevenyearold civil war 
against the government 
about 250 sri lankan police and soldiers are in the garrison 
which has survived on supplies dropped from highflying aircraft 
it was unclear whether the forces would try to lift the siege or 
whether the fort would be evacuated 
officials said one man in the fort was killed by rebel fire 
tuesday raising the garrisons casualties to nine in the past 
month 
wijeratne briefing colombobased diplomats wednesday said he 
proposed evacuating the fort and handing it over to the 
international committee of the red cross 
he said the red cross agreed to the plan and was waiting for 
authorization from the government to discuss it with the rebels 
</TEXT>
