pat bryden has performed thousands of 
marriages but wednesdays ceremony was different it was her own 
ms bryden 58 is the marriage registrar at gretna the 
scottish village known worldwide as the place where eloping couples 
crossed the english border to tie the knot 
for her marriage to expoliceman archie smith however she 
chose to walk down the aisle in nearby st andrews church 
although ive married thousands of couples over the years i 
never thought it would happen to me im very very happy said 
the bride who wore a blue suit with a pleated skirt and a pink hat 
about 100 wellwishers greeted the couple outside the church 
which was filled with 200 guests 
i was hoping for a quiet wedding but it wasnt to be pat is 
too wellknown said smith 59 
smiths wife rita died in 1988 and a few weeks later his home 
in the scottish town of lockerbie burned down in the wreckage of 
pan am flight 103 which was blown up in flight by a terrorist 
bomb ms bryden a longtime family friend went to console him 
and his two children and love blossomed 
he needed a lot of support at that time she said i was 
there with him 
changing laws and social mores have made it much easier to marry 
in britain and young lovers no longer arrive breathless with angry 
parents in hot pursuit 
the romantic allure lingers however and gretna still attracts 
some 1400 couples a year making ms bryden one of the worlds 
busiest marriage registrars 
ms bryden who had never married has worked in the gretna 
registry service for about 40 years twenty years ago she was 
authorized to perform marriages and has officiated at about 10000 
her office is in a small building which also houses a dentists 
office and couples sometimes recite their vows to the whine of a 
dentists drill 
from a legal point of view theres nothing special about 
gretna couples could wed just as easily anywhere else in scotland 
but they come here for the romance ms bryden said 
the villages associations with love and marriage ensure their 
wedding will be something different something to remember all 
their lives she said 
gretnas romantic associations date back to 1754 when an act of 
parliament outlawed irregular marriages in england no longer 
could couples simply declare themselves married in front of 
witnesses they had to publish banns a delcaration of the 
intended marriage and those under 21 needed parental consent 
the law did not apply in scotland so eloping couples headed up 
the main road from carlisle to glasgow crossing the river sark 
which marks the boundary of england and scotland 
irregular marriages were banned in scotland in 1940 but the 
marriage industry flourished as a registry office was opened in 
gretna 
until the 1970s when england reduced the marriage age from 21 
to 18 thousands of runaways came to scotland 
there is usually a waiting list for wedding dates at the 
registry office but work has started on a new office that will 
more than double the capacity to 3000 weddings a year the 
registrar intends to stay at her post 
gretna will always be a place of romance ms bryden said 
adding i think more and more people will come here to wed in the 
future 
she receives letters and cards from satisfied customers all 
over the world now that she too is taking the plunge she joked 
i now understand why brides get nervous as their big day 
approaches 
