<TEXT>
ward sims a veteran associated press 
writer whose career included stints as correspondent in juneau and 
fairbanks and bureau chief in anchorage died wednesday in seattle 
he was 65 
sims who retired in 1984 after more than three decades with the 
news agency had been flown to seattles providence medical center 
on aug 15 after suffering a heart attack at his home in sitka 
he had been doing very well said his wife virginia 
suddenly things began to go downhill he died peacefully and 
quickly 
he spent his entire professional career with the associated 
press joining the agency in san francisco in 1950 following his 
graduation from montana state university 
sims was born in tacoma wash and served in the army in europe 
during world war ii 
sims became correspondent in tacoma in 1951 and later that year 
transferred to seattle in 1960 he was assigned alaska statehouse 
correspondent in juneau assisted by his wife 
in 1968 he transferred to the philadelphia bureau and a year 
later became a general desk editor in new york he returned to 
alaska to open a fairbanks bureau in 1977 and a year later became 
chief of bureau in anchorage 
one of the biggest stories he covered was the 1964 earthquake 
that devastated anchorage valdez and other parts of southcentral 
alaska sims was the aps first reporter on the scene and he spent 
weeks covering the disaster 
his last byline for the news service was on a retrospective 
article about the disaster which was published last year on the 
earthquakes 25th anniversary 
after his retirement sims moved to sitka where he enjoyed 
fishing and hunting and was active in the rotary club he also was 
a writing coach at the juneau empire 
hes probably forgotten more than any of us will ever know 
about ap style and reporting in general said carl sampson 
managing editor of the juneau empire 
but it went beyond that we used ward as a resource when we 
had a difficult story wed call for ideas and suggestions we 
called him our dutch uncle every newspaper needs someone like 
him 
he was a super writer and a wonderful reporter said bill 
tobin sims predecessor in juneau and now editorial page editor of 
the anchorage times 
he was highly respected by everyone he dealt with 
in addition to his wife sims is survived by a son dixon of 
fairbanks 
