<TEXT>
some people sit on a sofa others may 
call the same piece of furniture a davenport a 
chesterfield or a settee 
your word choice says something distinctive about your identity 
the words we use and how we pronounce them make us special and 
identifiable as part of a group said william a kretzschmar an 
associate professor in the university of georgias english 
department who has devoted his career to chronicling the 
distinguishing features of the spoken word 
language marks us he said it gives us a sense of 
community and culture 
kretzschmar is editorinchief of two linguistic atlases that 
will contain the results of 60 years of research on how americans 
talk in two regions of the country 
the linguistic atlas of the middle and south atlantic states 
plots the use of language in 11 states stretching from new york to 
northern florida the linguistic atlas of the northcentral states 
covers six states from michigan to kentucky and parts of ontario 
canada 
the first of the two volumes is expected to published within two 
years kretzchmar said wednesday 
the atlases are part of a project to survey all of the united 
states and canada to document distinct areas of dialect 
the project is an extension of research performed in the 1930s 
and 1940s when specially trained interviewers documented the 
differences in speech among people in different parts of the 
country 
more than 1200 people in 500 communities in the southeast were 
interviewed and recorded during that period 
depending upon where you live you mmight call a mosquitoeating 
insect commonly found in wet areas a skeeter hawk snake 
doctor or dragonfly 
and a device for carrying water might be a pail bucket 
or piggin 
