<TEXT>
the international committee of the red cross is 
treading gingerly in the gulf crisis fearing to anger iraq by 
concentrating on the fate of western hostages 
highlighting its precarious position was prime minister margaret 
thatchers accusation that the icrc had failed to act to protect 
the thousands of trapped foreigners 
there was no direct comment from the allswiss agency 
traditionally pledged to confidentiality in its role as impartial 
monitor of the geneva conventions 
a spokesman merely noted that the icrc has been in touch with 
all states concerned since early august to ensure protection of the 
civilian population in both iraq and kuwait 
the head of the agencys middle east section flew to baghdad 
monday with a personal message from icrc president cornelio 
sommaruga dealing with all issues of humanitarian concern 
sources familiar with committee thinking said its first aim is 
to continue practical work to help all people requiring assistance 
focusing on the trapped westerners would raise doubts about its 
neutral stand the sources added 
the icrc has been seeking authority to visit kuwait to find out 
about the medical food and other needs of the population it has 
also been seeking to gain access to foreign nationals but without 
success 
the text of the 1949 geneva convention on the protection of 
civilians suggests that iraq is clearly in violation of its 
provisions iraq joined the convention in 1956 
but so far the icrc has stopped short of saying so publicly 
by the announced transfer of foreigners to strategic locations 
baghdad violated article 28 stipulating that the presence of a 
protected person may not be used to render certain points or areas 
immune from military operations 
a 1977 additional protocol elaborates on that but neither iraq 
nor the united states has ratified it 
the text says the presence or movement of civilians shall not 
be used in attempts to shield military objectives from attacks 
or to shield favor or impede military operations 
the 1949 convention says the taking of hostages is 
prohibited and that all aliens must be free to leave the 
territory of a party to a conflict unless their departure is 
contrary to the national interests of the state 
internees must not be held in areas particularly exposed to 
the dangers of war and they have the right to be visited by icrc 
delegates a special section dealing with occupied territories 
includes a prohibition of individual or mass transfers of 
persons from there to the territory of the occupying power 
kuwait is an occupied territory according to a un security 
council resolution but so far iraq has not allowed icrc delegates 
to visit there 
the section on occupied territories has been cited by the icrc 
on repeated occasions in denouncing israels policies in the west 
bank and gaza strip 
but the organizations position in israel is relatively strong 
because the jewish state cannot afford the bad publicity of barring 
the 42 icrc delegates working there 
in contrast any public stand by the icrc against iraq might 
spell an end to its humanitarian mission in the gulf crisis 
sources familiar with icrc concepts said the agency has to be 
pragmatic and that it must not risk blocking its work for a 
question of principle its baghdad delegation includes 37 members 
the sources who declined to be identified further said the 
icrc had to maintain credible neutrality in this confrontation and 
to stress that it is not an instrument of western or any other 
governments 
the geneva conventions say it is up to signatory governments to 
make sure they are respected 
the decision by neutral switzerland a nonun member to join 
the un sanctions against iraq has increased difficulties for the 
icrc the agency is known to have had serious misgivings when the 
bern government proposed joining the world body a proposal that 
was overwhelmingly defeated in a 1986 referendum 
</TEXT>
