they come from the mountain region they are hunters they do 
woodcutting theyve fought bears in the woods they know how to do 
the work without being told its almost automatic he said 
kirgan 51 should know an apache firefighter for 30 years he 
still can pass the strenuous step test a physical fitness 
requirement 
indians always have been firefighters on their own land but it 
wasnt until after world war ii that they turned to firefighting 
for the us government as a source of income 
people were back from the war and employment was down said 
kirgan they were living off the land and they were trying to get 
some income so they started organizing 
the mescaleros apaches of southern new mexico were the first 
indian firefighters to be exported when they were sent to help 
battle a california fire in 1948 kirgan said the bureau of indian 
affairs trained them gave them hard hats and sent them to work 
alongside the forest service crews 
they were so good that other states just started calling 
kirgan said in new mexico each spring 150 to 200 mescalero 
apaches apply for firefighting jobs about 50 are hired and go 
through three days of training they then are on call 24 hours a 
day if called to a fire they may work 12 to 16hour shifts for 
14 days without a break base pay is 798 an hour 
its seasonal undependable and dangerous work but for indians 
like clemente toledo summer firefighting is an important source of 
income 
you make more money in fewer hours at a faster pace said 
toledo 32 who grows corn and chili on his farm and works at odd 
