<TEXT>
youre watching an interesting documentary on 
pollution of a kentucky river switch channels and come back a few 
minutes later to find a yuppie rap video on the same station 
dont worry theres nothing wrong with your set its just tom 
weinberg testing the limits of television 
weinberg is executive producer of the 90s an hourlong 
showcase of independent videotape makers and producers that zips 
through topics such as politics religion the environment and 
culture at a pace designed to dazzle but never bore its viewers 
the weekly collage now in its second run of 13 shows is sent 
to more than 90 public and cable television stations across the 
country many of them run it between 10 pm and midnight 
the time slots dont seem to bother weinberg and his cohorts 
who are having fun with their latest attempt to alter the message 
and the medium 
part of it is we want to change the world in ways that make it 
more fun more humane more responsive says weinberg 46 who 
has a 1960s social conscience and a 1990s love for technology 
part of it is that its an incredibly absorbing pastime the 
process of making tv 
the television theyre making is not like standard commercial 
television or the other avantgarde shows on public stations the 
advent of a new generation of inexpensive but sophisticated video 
cameras has enabled tvquality production of unconventional 
lowbudget pieces and even amateur contributions 
one program includes panamanians speaking out about the us 
invasion of their country a look at the destruction of brazilian 
rain forests and a segment on residents of a chicago public housing 
project 
another includes a report on prochoice and antiabortion forces 
demonstrating outside a los angeles abortion clinic a fathers 
conversation with his cerebral palsystricken daughter a wacky 
piece on three women who call themselves the advice ladies and 
offer their wisdom free on the streets of new york city and a 
caustic look at pat boone and a minister reminiscing about boones 
miracle rescue from a bad investment 
segments can run from 10 seconds to 10 minutes the material is 
cut spliced and interposed with graphics at the whim of the 
producers 
its very different rougher says kevin harris program 
director for public television stations wgbh and wgbx in boston 
the subject matter is really all over the place 
weinberg says viewers are supposed to enjoy the show at whatever 
level they can understand and appreciate 
theres a lot of nuance and you interpret it differently than 
i do he says 
he and his small staff produce the 90s in a small downtown 
office filled with overnight delivery envelopes and stacks of 
videotapes they sift through 30 to 40 tapes a week 
the works come from many sources independent producers looking 
for an outlet for their work unsolicited contributions and 
correspondents under contract to produce segments for the program 
the finished product is presented to the public television 
system by sponsoring station kbdi in denver the home of weinberg 
colleague john schwartz whose screen credit is chief 
bureaucrat it also is fed via satellite to cable stations 
the first 13 episodes were fed in november through january with 
a commitment to be run on 25 pbs stations a 350000 grant from a 
corporation for public broadcastingpublic broadcasting service 
fund will ensure a third season with at least 13 new shows and a 
broader pbs audience weinberg says 
grants from the john d and catherine t macarthur foundation 
helped the show get started 
weinberg a chicago native with a penchant for cigars greasy 
cheeseburgers and the chicago white sox got an mba from new york 
university in the late 60s and worked at the family bakery before 
getting involved in video in the early 70s 
he helped found tvtv a group of filmmakers and producers who 
made their mark with a pair of video documentaries about the 1972 
democratic and republican national conventions that gained critical 
notice 
later he helped found the center for new television a 
notforprofit haven in chicago that provides resources for video 
producers 
weinberg also created image union a locally produced 
awardwinning pbs program featuring short works by independent 
filmmakers and producers 
weinberg might be doing something that no one else is but he 
might not be able to reach mass audiences 
there is so little invention and so much convention in 
television says j fred mcdonald curator of the museum of 
broadcast communication in chicago there is not much room for 
artistry in an inventive sort of way 
harris says the 90s will never capture a large audience 
even on public television 
if it really was broad enough to get a lot of exposure it 
wouldnt be the kind of show it is he said 
but others believe weinberg may yet win the influence he wants 
and just might influence what people are doing on television 
</TEXT>
