<TEXT>
the sinking of the uss indianapolis and the 
subsequent courtmartial of its captain constitute the us navys 
worst moral disaster as well its worst sea disaster said the 
author of a new book on the affair 
journalist dan kurzman author of fatal voyage contends 
capt charles mcvay was made a scapegoat to mask mismanagement by 
high navy officials in the tragedy that claimed 880 lives in the 
closing days of world war ii 
a japanese submarine torpedoed the unescorted cruiser in the 
western pacific ocean on july 30 1945 after the ship had 
delivered components for the hiroshima atomic bomb to tinian island 
in the northern marianas 
for five days survivors clung to a few life rafts or bobbed in 
life jackets as dehydration exposure and swarming sharks killed 
hundreds of their companions military officials did not know the 
ship had gone down and the survivors were found by chance 
mcvay a highly decorated admirals son became the first 
captain ever tried by the us navy for losing a ship in battle 
in a highly publicized courtmartial he was found guilty of 
gross negligence for failing to maintain his ship on a zigzag 
or antisubmarine course even though mcvays orders did not 
require him to zigzag 
i think he was railroaded theres no other word for it they 
simply wanted to protect their own necks kurzman said in a 
telephone interview from new jersey 
fortyfive years later mcvays family is still fighting to 
clear his name kurzman hopes his book will help them 
kurzman conducted more than 100 interviews and reviewed 
thousands of navy documents to write his tale of mcvay and the 
horrifying days his men spent in the ocean between guam and the 
philippines the torpedo hits sank the indianapolis within 15 
minutes and about 800 of the ships 1196 crewmen were able to 
abandon ship the cruiser sent an sos but its radio apparently had 
been knocked out 
the men initially were confident of rescue but watched in 
frustration as planes passed high overhead without spotting them 
for the most part they were without food or fresh water 
delirium set in after a day and some men began attacking other 
survivors others died in agony after drinking sea water some 
believing there was a spigot with fresh water several feet down 
tore off life jackets and dove down never to resurface still 
others swam toward imaginary islands or dove to underwater hotels 
at night sharks would swim off with dozens of the men leaving 
only bloody streaks on the oily water 
no one thought to check for the indianapolis when it failed to 
arrive at leyte and no highlevel navy officer was disciplined for 
failing to respond 
survivors might never have been found had not a plane on an 
antisubmarine patrol spotted an oil streak left by the sunken 
ship only 316 men survived the ordeal 
kurzman said navy officials desperate for a scapegoat quickly 
fixed blame on mcvay son of former us asiatic fleet commander 
adm charles mcvay ii 
against the recommendation of adm chester nimitz commander in 
chief of the us pacific fleet who said mcvays failure to 
order a zigzag course was an error in judgment but not of such 
nature as to constitute gross negligence secretary of the navy 
james forrestal ordered that mcvay be courtmartialed 
kurzman said his book contains new information proving that 
mcvay was wrongly tried he uncovered a navy document that admits 
the charge of failing to zigzag probably had nothing to do with the 
loss of the ship one memo characterized the charge as 
supertechnical 
testimony by the japanese sub commander flown in from japan by 
the prosecution and an expert witness for the defense suggested 
that zigzagging probably would not have saved the indianapolis 
the navy had information that four japanese submarines were 
operating between guam and the philippines one had sunk the 
destroyer uss underhill six days earlier kurzman said that 
information could have alerted mcvay to be more cautious but it 
never reached the captain or the routing officers on guam who sent 
the indianapolis out unescorted 
the information was kept under wraps for security reasons 
kurzman said 
kurzman said information that might have cleared mcvay was 
edited out of public documents and the navy has refused to release 
it 
found by the navy to be unfit to ever command a vessel again 
mcvay was assigned to a shore job in new orleans he was 
transferred to the retired list in 1949 with the rank of rear 
admiral because of earlier combat citations but he never escaped 
the ghosts of the indianapolis he was haunted by letters and 
telephone calls from dead crewmens relatives who blamed him for 
their loved ones deaths 
my father hated to open his mail on any given holiday said 
his son kimo wilder mcvay a promoter in honolulu usually these 
cards said something like if it werent for you my son brother 
etc would be with us this easter christmas fathers day etc 
the elder mcvay plagued by a number of personal problems shot 
himself in the head with his service revolver in the front yard of 
his litchfield conn home in 1968 
a white house assistant told kimo mcvay in 1983 that no 
authority exists for the secretary of the navy to change the 
findings of the courtmartial and said presidential pardons are not 
awarded posthumously 
their argument is theres no precedent but theres no 
precedent to the fact that hes the only us captain 
courtmartialed for losing a ship in battle that isnt 
democracy kurzman said if theres no machinery then create 
it 
</TEXT>
