firm and collective response to the naked act of aggression 
perpetrated by iraq and added 
american determination to resist saddam husseins bid for 
power sends a powerful signal to the world that ruthless tyrants 
cannot violate international law with impunity nor attempt too 
hold the worlds oil supply hostage to their will 
the rev emilio castro general secretary of the world council 
of churches said in a statement in geneva the council opposes 
strongly iraqs seizure of kuwait and supports the uns firm 
stand and action about it 
urging the arab league to go further in mediating the 
conflict castro said we call on all nations concerned to 
exercise patience and good will by refraining from use of force or 
show of force 
the rev j bryan hehir a roman catholic specialist on 
international affairs of georgetown university commended the un 
call for sanctions and said deployment of us and other troops 
could be regarded a means of preserving peace rather than 
aggravating hositlities 
you can argue that the movement of forces is designed to be a 
deterrent to further aggression he told catholic news service 
in that sense i think thats wise 
robert t hennemeyer director for justice and peace of the us 
catholic conference in washington said us church officials 
regard this as a clear case of aggression that thereby would meet 
the just war criteria 
by that criteria he noted a nation is justified in helping a 
friend attacked unjustly 
evangelist billy graham endorsing bushs call for prayer said 
the persian gulf situation is potentially one of the most 
dangerous threats to world peace and stability since world war ii 
upheavals there also could have major spiritual 
implications he said these events are happening in that part 
of the world where history began and the bible says where 
history as we know it will some day end 
let us pray that god will give wisdom to all those leaders 
whose decisions can make a difference there he said let us 
pray also that god will intervene and bring peace to that troubled 
region 
