<DOCNO> AP900822-0210 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
she first went into therapy for help with some marital and 
childhood issues 
i had no idea vietnam affected me until around six years 
ago she said 
she and her husband divorced in 1983 partly due to the war 
i closed the book on vietnam when i got back like everybody 
else did she said my husband had been a war protester and we 
never talked about vietnam he was not comfortable talking about 
it neither was anybody else in the country 
at the vietnam reunion in new york city six years ago the 
whole thing started opening up everything started coming to the 
surface she said just after she arrived she got a throbbing 
headache that lasted for a day and a half until she threw up 
i felt better after i did that she said its taken me a 
long time i would have physical responses to thinking about 
vietnam or talking about vietnam that would last sometimes for a 
couple of weeks now i have a little bit of an emotional response 
after i talk about vietnam 
ms rankin herself is a psychotherapist while in vietnam she 
will do some construction work but she also will serve as the team 
shrink coleading a discussion group 
she is one of hundreds of veterans returning in recent years to 
try to sort out the real war as well as the war in their minds 
it profoundly affected your life whether youre conscious of 
it or not she said i think many of us who make that 
pilgrimage back become conscious that it affected our lives and 
theres something we havent resolved or havent put to rest i 
think people go back to do that 
