mail to district offices that can work with businesses on a local 
basis 
the vast majority of employers are perfectly willing to adhere 
to the law but an awful lot of them dont understand what the 
provisions are because it is used so seldomly said john tieso of 
the labor departments division of veterans reemployment rights 
under the law reservists called out of the civilian work force 
must be treated like any worker on an unpaid leave of absence when 
they return businesses large and small must give them their old 
jobs back or ones of equal stature with full seniority 
in addition reservists are due any increase in pay or benefits 
that other workers received while they were gone but the law also 
gives employers the right to lay off a reservist if it can show the 
job was eliminated while he or she was away at duty 
though employers arent required to provide medical benefits 
many allow reservists to continue coverage if they pay their own 
premiums 
theres a good possibility that corporate coverage is better 
than government coverage said one officer who asked not to be 
identified 
reservists who serve more than 30 days are covered by the 
militarys medical plan a potential problem arises tieso said 
for those who serve under one month 
many businesses that have called the labor and defense 
departments to check on the law have indicated theyll continue 
medical benefits for reservists during the initial 30day period 
in a relatively unknown situation where they dont know how 
long its going to be it could be five days 15 days or 150 days 
some employers are simply saying hey dont worry about it 
well take care of it until you get home tieso said 
so far employers arent balking over the law tieso said most 
of them want to make it easier for these guys to go off to service 
its a nice way to do business he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

