<TEXT>
a synthetic hormone that can boost milk 
production in dairy cows by 10 percent to 25 percent has cleared 
all the safety testing it needs and merits approval for commercial 
use doctors say in a medical journal 
the hormone bovine somatotropin or bst has been banned 
temporarily in two states but the doctors wrote in wednesdays 
journal of the american medical association that it causes no 
changes in milk composition of any practical importance to 
consumers 
the minor differences in milk composition shown between 
unsupplemented and bstsupplemented cows are well within normal 
biological variation in milk composition they wrote 
the authors dr william h daughaday of washington university 
school of medicine in st louis and david m barbano of the food 
science department at cornell university in ithaca ny each have 
done consulting or research work under grants from one of its four 
manufacturers monsanto co the journal said 
however an editorial by an outside researcher concurred with 
their conclusions saying milk produced from cows treated with 
bovine somatotropin is no different from the milk of untreated 
cows 
it is both inappropriate and wrong for specialinterest groups 
to play on the health and safety fears of the public to further 
their own ends said the editorial by charles h grossman an 
immunologist at the department of veterans affairs in cincinnati 
daughaday and barbano noted that the food and drug 
administration pronounced the hormone safe in 1985 and could 
approve its commercial use by next year a possibility that has 
raised concerns among groups opposed to genetic engineering 
the hormone is produced by a method similar to that used to make 
synthetic human insulin 
critics say not enough research has been done to be sure milk 
produced by cows injected with the animal hormone would be safe for 
people 
grossman said hysterical reaction produced laws in wisconsin 
and minnesota temporarily barring the use of bst for at least a 
year 
however in january the chairman of the senate agriculture 
committee sen patrick leahy dvt called for an investigation 
of the fdas review of the hormone after allegations that the 
review had been inadequate 
