<TEXT>
a federal judge supervising an overhaul of the 
manville trust fund for the first time limited fees to plaintiffs 
lawyers for settling claims involving asbestosrelated diseases 
us district judge jack b weinstein who has ordered an 
overhaul of the cashstrapped trust tuesday limited the amount 
lawyers can charge clients to 20 percent of settlements in 
emergency cases 
weinstein last month froze all payments by the trust pending a 
reorganization plan except to victims who can demonstrate financial 
or medical hardship the freeze is in place until sept 6 when a 
financial restructuring plan is due 
an estimated one third of more than 1 billion paid to asbestos 
victims since the trust was established in 1988 has gone to 
attorneys handling the cases limits on payment arrangements 
between attorneys and their clients was not ordered when the trust 
was formed as part of manville corps bankruptcy reorganization 
weinstein has been highly critical of the amount received by 
lawyers and had promised to reduce the payments so victims could 
receive more money in the future 
the matter of fees is now being considered in connection with 
a restructuring of the trusts payment program weinstein wrote 
in his order ongoing discussions with representative plaintiffs 
lawyers are continuing 
the fee cap applies only to hardship claim settlements under 
which claimants must prove extreme financial need based on number 
of dependents disease prognosis prior settlements assets and 
liabilities and other income 
under weinsteins ruling for settlements paid out over time 
the 20 percent fee limit may be collected only as each payment is 
received so that victims or their families always receive 80 
percent of each check 
attorneys were expected to challenge the cap many plaintiffs 
lawyers have argued they have earned the amount charged by virtue 
of more than a decade of work by some attorneys in the asbestos 
litigation 
the judge had made it clear that he anticipated some type of 
reduction though i think the reduction is more than is justified 
given the amount fo work that goes into these cases said stanley 
levy a leading asbestos plaintiffs lawyer 
it also raises the question of whether he really has the 
authority to interfere in the contractual relationship between a 
client and the attorney levy said 
us bankruptcy judge burton lifland who presided over the 
manville reorganization refused to impose a limit on attorneys 
fees no other judge has sought such a limit before 
the trust to date has settled close to 24000 claims for more 
than 1 billion from people with lung cancer and other respiratory 
diseases caused by inhaling asbestos fibers mostly during 
shipbuilding and other construction 
but the trust faces 130000 more claims it cant meet and has 
paid only two thirds of the money it owes in settled cases the 
reorganization order came after the trust said it was out of money 
to pay new claims it said would not be met until well into the 21st 
century 
the trust also is under fire for a decision to hire a public 
relations firm on a 10000 monthly retainer with a 15000 monthly 
cap the trust has paid the firm robinson lake lerer and 
montgomery about 30000 so far 
it is unclear whether the payments violate weinsteins freeze on 
payments but the judge has been notified about the public 
relations firms hiring one of his law clerks said tuesday 
the trust eventually is expected to be consolidated with a group 
of asbestosmaking companies that say they cant meet asbestos 
claims into a single classaction lawsuit before weinstein 
