<TEXT>
the boeing co has taken its insurance companies 
to court in a bid to settle an 80 million dispute over who should 
pay to clean up toxic wastes at two seattlearea sites 
the insurance companies have refused to pay for cleanup closts 
they contend boeing knew it was polluting western processing in 
kent and queen city farms in maple valley 
but during opening statements in court tuesday boeing attorneys 
told a us district court jury that the aircraft manufacturer 
never expected its practices would cause widespread pollution at 
the sites 
boeing believes its insurance policies should have been 
honored and they have not been said robert sayler an attorney 
for the company 
boeing has told its insurers it could be liable for cleanup 
costs at 13 sites in six states which could run into hundreds of 
millions of dollars 
boeing dumped 24 million gallons of liquid wastes into pits at 
western processing and queen city farms 
in the 1980s the company agreed to pay the bulk of the cleanup 
costs more than 80 million at the sites under courtordered 
consent decrees with the federal environmental protection agency 
sayler said boeing began using queen city farms in 1957 because 
it preferred a remote lagoon over dumping its wastes in the 
duwamish river or puget sound boeing had been barging its wastes 
to sea for dumping before 1957 said charles gordon another 
company attorney 
in 1964 gordon said boeing began taking its wastes to western 
processing because that company was recycling the state also 
recommended the move 
boeing never anticipated the problems that would occur at the 
sites and the companys decisions must be viewed in the context of 
environmental standards that have evolved over the years sayler 
and gordon told the jury 
the insurance companies named as defendants include aetna 
casualty amp surety co hartford accident amp indemnity co insurance 
co of north american and ronald e smith amp cos an association of 
syndicates that includes lloyds of london 
