<TEXT>
crude oil futures soared above 30 a barrel for 
the first time in nearly five years wednesday as traders reacted 
to fears of military escalation in the middle east showdown 
nervous trading also pushed unleaded gasoline futures to a 
record high closing price 
analysts said world supplies were starting to feel the crunch of 
4 million barrels of crude lost each day through the boycott of 
iraq and kuwait the saudi arabians also curtailed some previously 
arranged sales of jet fuel and other products to accommodate the 
massive military buildup on their soil 
the main factor here in the crude market apart from a concern 
of hostilities is simply the fact that opec continues to drag its 
feet in getting higher production said bob baker an analyst 
with prudentialbache securities inc 
indications that saudi arabia and venezuela want to increase 
production have not materialized into any more oil 
the price of october contracts for light sweet crude shot up 
251 per 42gallon barrel to close at 3122 on the new york 
mercantile exchange oil last traded above the 30 threshold on 
nov 26 1985 
unleaded gasoline prices on the merc closed at 1043 per gallon 
for september delivery up 299 cents over tuesdays record close 
of 1013 per gallon the nearterm contract has closed higher for 
six straight trading days 
those following the industry said consumers will be paying even 
more for gasoline at the pump although analysts said there was no 
firm way to translate the rise in futures prices to a predictable 
rise in retail prices 
one analyst said a 1cent rise in unleaded futures can mean a 
1cent increase at the pump 
wall street traders were generally surprised by the abrupt jump 
of crude over the 30 per barrel mark 
as long as this standoff continued i had expected pretty 
volatile markets in the 25 to 30 range said stephen smith an 
