<TEXT>
a growing supply of pork and a break in cash market prices 
combined wednesday to send hog futures prices skidding at the 
chicago mercantile exchange 
pork bellies also were big losers with the contract for 
delivery in august falling the limit 2 cents a pound for the second 
straight day 
on other markets petroleum futures surged ahead strongly 
grains and soybeans were mostly higher and gold advanced 
hog futures were dragged lower by the nearby october contract 
which was down as much as 110 cents a pound 
that contract reflected a fairly substantial break in fresh 
pork loins this week and in cash hogs said charles levitt 
senior livestock analyst for shearson lehman hutton inc 
in addition theres a seasonal increase in hogs being brought 
to market thats causing some supply problems he said 
bellie futures were undercut by two days of sharp declines in 
the price of fresh pork bellies 
an added problem for pork prices may appear friday when the usda 
issues its monthly cold storage report 
this report could show a very large supply of turkeys in 
storage levitt said if it does there could be some cheap 
turkeys around that could compete with some of the pork products 
during the fall and winter holiday seasons 
cattle prices settled higher rebounding from losses suffered 
after a government report last week showed a large increase in 
cattle placed on feed lots 
the big increase was in july and these animals wont be coming 
to market until the end of the year 
well still have some tightness this fall said levitt 
live cattle settled 15 cent to 42 cent higher with the 
contract for delivery in october at 7822 cents a pound feeder 
cattle were 35 cent lower to 35 cent higher with august at 8952 
cents a pound live hogs were 75 cent lower to 02 cent higher 
with october at 4855 cents a pound and frozen pork bellies were 
60 cent to the limit 2 cents lower with august at 4572 cents a 
pound 
deepening fears on the middle east crisis sent oil futures 
soaring past the 30 mark on the new york mercantile exchange for 
the first time since nov 26 1985 
west texas intermediate crude oil advanced the limit 1 on the 
distant contracts to 251 on the october delivery which settled 
at 3122 a barrel heating oil was 431 cents to 764 cents higher 
with september at 9135 cents a gallon and unleaded gasoline was 
295 cents to 566 cents higher with september at 10411 a gallon 
precious metals futures advanced on the commodity exchange in 
new york but lacked the volitility of previous days despite sharp 
movements in oil prices 
the situation in the middle east is too uncertain said john 
oconnell manager of futures research for refco inc in new york 
most of the guys trading in gold have turned a little 
cautious he said any fall in crude could hurt them as well 
gold futures settled 330 to 4 higher with the august contract 
at 411 a troy ounce 
grain and soybean futures prices were mostly a little higher on 
the chicago board of trade 
trading was mixed and sluggish through much of the session but 
prices improved on the belief that the soviet union is in the 
market for cooking oil 
rumors surfaced late the day that the russians were buying or 
interested in buying bottled vegetable oil from south america 
said victor lespinasse an assistant vice president with dean 
witter reynolds inc 
